$\begin{align}
\dfrac{1}{ v}&=\dfrac{1}{\greenD f}-\dfrac{1}{\redD u}
\end{align}$

Substituting the values of $\greenD f$ and $\redD u$ above, we get the image distance $v$,

$\begin{align}
\dfrac{1}{ v}&=\dfrac{1}{(\greenD{-15\ \text{cm}})}-\dfrac{1}{(\redD{-12\ \text{cm}})}\\\\
&=\dfrac{(\redD{-12\ \text{cm}})-(\greenD{-15\ \text{cm}})}{(\greenD{-15\ \text{cm}})\times (\redD{-12\ \text{cm}})}\\\\
&=\dfrac{\cancel{3}\ \cancel{\text{cm}}}{(\stackrel{5}{\cancel{15}}\ \cancel{\text{cm}})\times (12\ \text{cm})}\\\\
&=\dfrac{1}{+60\ \text{cm}}\\\\
\Rightarrow  v&=+60\ \text{cm}
\end{align}$

